Relevant captured text from People article, "Jeffrey Epstein's Alleged Suicide Note Is Unsealed by Federal Judge," by Charmaine Patterson, published May 6, 2026 9:01 PM EDT.

The article subheading states: "The document, which is not dated or signed, has not been verified."

Need-to-know bullets state:
- Jeffrey Epstein died in his jail cell on Aug. 10, 2019 while awaiting trial on sex trafficking charges. His death was later ruled a suicide.
- Last month, the financier's cellmate alleged to authorities that Epstein may have left a suicide note.
- A federal judge unsealed the alleged note on Wednesday, May 6; however, the note is undated, unsigned and has not been verified.

The article states that on Wednesday, May 6, District Judge Kenneth Karas of the Southern District of New York unsealed what appears to be a handwritten note from Epstein. It reports that the note begins, "They investigated me for month[s] - Found NOTHING!!!" and that Epstein then allegedly referenced years-old charges, adding, "It is a treat to be able to choose one's time to say goodbye." It reports that he concluded, "Watcha want me to do - Bust out cryin!! NO FUN - NOT WORTH IT."

The article identifies an image captioned "Jeffrey Epstein's alleged suicide note" and credits it to the U.S. District Court Southern District of New York.

The article states that the release came about a week after a petition from the New York Times to the court, and after Epstein's former cellmate Nicholas Tartaglione's claim to authorities that Epstein had left a suicide note. Before release, according to the article, the note was locked in a courthouse in relation to Tartaglione's criminal case for the last seven years. The article reiterates that it is not dated or signed and has not been verified.

The article states that Tartaglione alleged he found the note inside a graphic novel in July 2019, just after Epstein was discovered on the floor of his cell with injuries to his neck; it further states that while Epstein previously told guards Tartaglione had tried to kill him, according to a Bureau of Prisons memo in the Epstein Files, he later recanted and said it was a suicide attempt. The article notes Tartaglione has long denied harming Epstein and is serving a life sentence for four murders.